{"id":"11323","name":"Google authenticator MFA code to clipboard","tagline":"Copies login code out of the authenticator app to clipboard so that you can paste them on any device","icon":"ios15 c4292093695 g59862","latest":"32836","description":"\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>This is for those who are fed up with having to open their phone, finding and opening the google authenticator app and then typing or copying the code manually to log into any service or for any other MFA purpose really.</p>\n<p>The shortcut opens the authenticator app, takes a screenshot, crops it to the size of the required code* and then extracts that text out of the image minus the space to the clipboard, so you can paste it on any device (if you have bluetooth enabled). </p>\n<p>Name the shortcut to whatever you want to tell Siri, for me it is \"University Login\", \"Work Login\" and \"Private Login\" for my three different MFA codes. </p>\n<p>*You likely have to <a href=\"https://imgur.com/HRXzK2k\">adjust the height</a> of where the crop should start (Crop -&gt; Y coordinate) as my phone screen might be a different size (iPhone 12 Pro Max). </p>\n<p>I used a full resolution screenshot airdropped to my Mac <a href=\"https://imgur.com/vuqIAR5\">in photoshop</a> to figure out my first code starts after 465 pixels. </p>\n<p>And if you have several codes like me simply duplicate the shortcut and change the name and pixels so it matches the second code and so on. I now have three shortcuts I can trigger via Siri so that the right code is in my clipboard when loggin in.</p>\n\t\t\t\t","releasenotes":"<p><strong>1.03 - April 23, 2022, 1:30 p.m.</strong></p><p>Ensures bluetooth is active before copying login code</p>"}